+This document explains how to create changelog entries for our **public** changelog (the hosted site investors and customers see). The changelog is hosted separately and entries are synced from your repository.
+
+**Not the same as:** pull requests, merge commits, or auto-generated git digests. Those are engineering artifacts. **Do not** publish internal commit-audit files (e.g. under `changelog/internal/`) to the public changelog.
+
+## Workflow: same format in every repo, then human review
+
+**Format is reusable:** Copy or share this guide (`.cursor/commands/changelog.md`) across **wolf-server**, **wolf-enterprise-frontend**, and any other repo that feeds the hosted changelog. Same MDX frontmatter, tags, sections, and bullet style → **same look on the public site** and the same rules for `wolf-changelog` sync.
+
+**Two separate tracks:**
+
+| Track | What it is | Who it’s for |
+|-------|------------|--------------|
+| **Public changelog** | Hand-written MDX in `changelog/` (repo root), per **Public site format** below | Investors, customers, partners |
+| **Internal audit** (optional) | Auto-generated `changelog/internal/from-main/` by day from `git log` | Engineers only — reminder of what merged, not vetted copy |
+
+**How the real changelog gets written (not automated):**
+
+1. **Review** merged work — **PR by PR** (read the diff / description) or **day by day** (batch PRs that merged on a given date), until you’re satisfied nothing user-visible is missed.
+2. **Write** one or more MDX files using this guide (title, description, What’s New / Improvements / Bug Fixes). Match the **release or communication date** you want on the site (often the merge day, or a single “release” covering several days). **If nothing merged to `main` on a calendar day, do not create a public entry for that day** — skip it.
+3. **Sync** to `wolf-changelog` / the hosted site as you do today.
+
+The internal generator does **not** replace step 1–2; it only helps you **remember** what dates had activity on `main` before you write the human entry.
 
